TikTok hides undesirable videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which - under 18 years of age
Imagine China / Reuters
The Guardian says that the Chinese social network TikTok censored with videos mentioning Tiananmen Square, Tibet's independence or the banned religious group Falun Gong.
The documents found in the publication say that the owner of TikTok (company ByteDance) with the help of the application promotes the foreign policy of China abroad.
The major part of the violations relating to China's policy falls under "incitement to hatred."
In each case, TikTok places undesirable publications in a context that is appropriate to general rules so that the actions of the social network do not look censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of the socialist system of China falls under the general ban "criticism or attacks on politics and social rules of any country, such as constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc."
The ban on mentioning incidents in Tiananmen Square or genocide in Cambodia falls under "digestion of the history of China or other countries."
The document also lists the list of banned names of twenty "foreign leaders or statesmen," including North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, American presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Pak Kain, President of Indonesia Jodno and President of Indonesia.
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Publications from the first category are removed by social network administrators and may result in blocking the user.
Not too severe violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited to TikTok algorithms.
ByteDance representatives told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer apply: "Now we use a localized approach for moderation, as well as attract independent local specialists."
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publications, says Rustem Bogdanov, co-founder of the "Producer Center."
"Producer Center" is one of Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Producer Center" coordinates with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be placed without agreement, Bogdanov reports.
When asked whether TikTok can speak about politics or Putin, Bogdanov responds affirmatively and says he has seen such publications.
Our Didgital founder Roman Zaripov agrees with Bogdanov: "The main rules for TikTok users are listed in the user agreement: it is impossible to post shocking content, discriminating statements and so on."
But under these rules you can sum up any content that does not like moderators, notes Zaripov.
Zaripov's agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which - under 18 years.
According to the user agreement, only persons over 13 years of age can use TikTok.
Social network administrators check their age with the help of artificial intelligence: neuronet analyzes the faces and determines how many years a person looks, says Bogdanov.
If the neuronet decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork co-working.
